name: Aruba - Balance Of Trade
description:
The quarterly net financial position of Aruba in the global goods and services market, measured as the difference in value between its imports and exports. A negative trade balance indicates imports exceed exports; a positive trade balance indicates exports exceed imports.

Units: AFI Million

Source: Aruba Central Bureau of Statistics

name: Aruba - Consumer Price Index Cpi
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2019=100

Source: Aruba Central Bureau of Statistics

name: Aruba - Inflation Rate
description:
The growth rate of the prices in Aruba.

Source: Aruba Central Bureau of Statistics

The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2010=100, NSA

Source: National Statistical Service of the Republic of Armenia

name: Belarus - Balance of Trade

Units: USD Million

Source: National Bank of the Republic of Belarus

name: Belarus - Current Account
description:
The the sum of the balance of trade (goods and services exports less imports), net income from abroad and net current transfers. A positive value indicates that a country is a net lender to the rest of the world; a negative value indicates that a country is a net borrower.

name: Belarus - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 1990M12=100, NSA

Source: National Statistical Committee of the Republic of Belarus

The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2018M12=100, NSA

Source: Bank of Botswana

The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

name: Ivory Coast - Consumer Price Index Cpi
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2014=100

Source: Intitut National de la Statistique

name: Cayman Islands - Consumer Price Index Cpi
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points Sept 2016=100

Source: Cayman Islands - The Economics & Statistics Office

Harmonized Indices of Consumer Prices (HICP) are economic indicators that provide official measures of consumer inflation in the Eurozone. These indices track changes in prices to consumer goods and services that are commonly purchased by households. The compilation methodology index is harmonized across EU countries.

Units: Index Points CPPY=100, NSA

Source: Czech Statistical Office

name: Czech Republic - Manufacturing PMI
description:
This monthly index tracks the health of the manufacturing sector in the Czech Republic. Private sector companies report improvement or deterioration in key quantitative indicators like new orders, production, inventories, and employment levels. Responses are amalgamated into an index whose value indicates expansion or contraction of the manufacturing sector. A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

Units: SA

name: Germany - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2015=100, NSA

Source: Federal Statistical Office

A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

name: Estonia - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 1997=100, NSA

name: European Union - Consumer Price Index (cpi)
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2015=100, NSA

name: Greece - Manufacturing PMI
description:
This monthly index tracks the health of the manufacturing sector in Greece. Private sector companies report improvement or deterioration in key quantitative indicators like new orders, production, inventories, and employment levels. Responses are amalgamated into an index whose value indicates expansion or contraction of the manufacturing sector. A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

Units: SA

Source: Markit

name: Guatemala - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2010=100, NSA

name: India - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2012=100, NSA

Source: Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation (MOSPI), India

A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. name: Sri Lanka - Manufacturing PMI
description:
This monthly index tracks the health of the manufacturing sector in Sri Lanka. Private sector companies report improvement or deterioration in key quantitative indicators like new orders, production, inventories, and employment levels. Responses are amalgamated into an index whose value indicates expansion or contraction of the manufacturing sector. A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

Source: Central Bank of Sri Lanka

name: Sri Lanka - Personal Income Tax Rate
description:

description:

Units: Million

name: Sri Lanka - Producer Prices
description:

Units: Index Points 2013 Q4=100, NSA

Source: Central Bank of Sri Lanka

name: Sri Lanka - Producer Prices Change
description:

Units: percent 2013 Q4=100, NSA

name: Sri Lanka - Household Saving Ratio
description:

name: Sri Lanka - Private Sector Credit

name: Lesotho - Balance of Trade

Units: LSL Million

name: Lesotho - Consumer Price Index Cpi
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2016M12=100

Source: Lesotho Bureau of Statistics

name: Latvia - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:

The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

name: Myanmar - Balance of Trade
description:
The monthly net financial position of Myanmar in the global goods and services market, measured as the difference in value between its imports and exports. A negative trade balance indicates imports exceed exports; a positive trade balance indicates exports exceed imports.

Units: USD Million

Source: Central Statistics Organization, Myanmar

name: Myanmar - Current Account
description:
The the sum of the balance of trade (goods and services exports less imports), net income from abroad and net current transfers. A positive value indicates that a country is a net lender to the rest of the world; a negative value indicates that a country is a net borrower.

Units: USD Million

Source: Central Bank of Myanmar

name: Myanmar - Current Account to GDP
description:
The current account balance of Myanmar expressed as a percentage of its GDP.

Units: percent

Source: Ministry of National Planning and Economic Development, Myanmar

name: Myanmar - Competitiveness Index
description:
A measurement of the level of productivity of Myanmar, based on a set of institutions, policies and other factors.

Units: Points

Source: World Economic Forum

name: Myanmar - Consumer Price Index Cpi
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2012=100

Source: Central Statistics Organization, Myanmar

name: Myanmar - Inflation Rate
description:
The growth rate of the prices in Myanmar.

Units: percent 2012=100

Source: Central Statistics Organization, Myanmar

name: Myanmar - Exports
description:
The total value of the goods and services produced by Myanmar and purchased by foreign entities.

Units: USD Million

Source: Central Statistics Organization, Myanmar

name: Myanmar - Foreign Direct Investment
description:
The value of all investments made by foreign entities directly into companies in Myanmar. It does not include foreign purchases of equities on domestic stock exchanges.

Units: USD Million

Source: Central Statistics Organization, Myanmar

name: Myanmar - GDP
description:
The unadjusted gross domestic product of Myanmar.

Units: USD Billion Current USD

Source: World Bank

name: Myanmar - GDP Annual Growth Rate
description:
The annual growth rate of GDP in Myanmar.

Units: percent

Source: Central Bank of Myanmar

name: Myanmar - Government Budget

Units: percent of GDP

Source: World Bank

GDP per capita in International dollars

Units: USD

Source: World Bank

name: Myanmar - Imports
description:

Units: USD Million

Units: percent

Source: Central Bank of Myanmar

name: Myanmar - Manufacturing PMI
description:
This monthly index tracks the health of the manufacturing sector in Myanmar. Private sector companies report improvement or deterioration in key quantitative indicators like new orders, production, inventories, and employment levels. Responses are amalgamated into an index whose value indicates expansion or contraction of the manufacturing sector. A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

Source: Markit Economics

The quarterly net financial position of Mauritania in the global goods and services market, measured as the difference in value between its imports and exports. A negative trade balance indicates imports exceed exports; a positive trade balance indicates exports exceed imports.

Units: MRO Billion

Source: ONS, Mauritania

name: Mauritania - Current Account
description:
The the sum of the balance of trade (goods and services exports less imports), net income from abroad and net current transfers. A positive value indicates that a country is a net lender to the rest of the world; a negative value indicates that a country is a net borrower.

Units: MRO Billion

Source: ONS, Mauritania

name: Mauritania - Current Account to GDP
description:
The current account balance of Mauritania expressed as a percentage of its GDP.

Units: percent

Source: Central Bank of Mauritania

name: Mauritania - Competitiveness Index
description:
A measurement of the level of productivity of Mauritania, based on a set of institutions, policies and other factors.

Units: Points

Source: World Economic Forum

name: Mauritania - Consumer Price Index Cpi
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2014=100, NSA

Source: Central Bank of Mauritania

description:

name: Netherlands - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:

It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

name: Nepal - Consumer Price Index Cpi
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

name: Pakistan - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2007/2008=100, NSA

description:

The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. name: Serbia - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2006=100, NSA

description:

name: Sweden - Manufacturing Production
description:

Units: percent WDA

Source: Eurostat

name: Sweden - Manufacturing PMI
description:
This monthly index tracks the health of the manufacturing sector in Sweden. Private sector companies report improvement or deterioration in key quantitative indicators like new orders, production, inventories, and employment levels. Responses are amalgamated into an index whose value indicates expansion or contraction of the manufacturing sector. A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

Units: SA

Source: Swedbank

name: Sweden - New Orders
description:
The market value of new orders of manufactured goods in Sweden by month.

Units: Index Points WDA, 2015=100

Source: Statistics Sweden

Source: Skatteverket

name: Sweden - Population
description:
The number of residents of Sweden.

Units: Million

Source: Eurostat

name: Sweden - Producer Prices
description:

name: Swaziland - Balance of Trade
description:
The quarterly net financial position of Swaziland in the global goods and services market, measured as the difference in value between its imports and exports. A negative trade balance indicates imports exceed exports; a positive trade balance indicates exports exceed imports.

Units: SZL Million

Source: Central Bank of Swaziland

name: Swaziland - Current Account
description:
The the sum of the balance of trade (goods and services exports less imports), net income from abroad and net current transfers. A positive value indicates that a country is a net lender to the rest of the world; a negative value indicates that a country is a net borrower.

Units: SZL Million

Source: Central Bank of Swaziland

name: Swaziland - Current Account to GDP
description:
The current account balance of Swaziland expressed as a percentage of its GDP.

Units: percent

Source: Central Bank of Swaziland

name: Swaziland - Competitiveness Index
description:
A measurement of the level of productivity of Swaziland, based on a set of institutions, policies and other factors.

Units: Points

Source: World Economic Forum

name: Swaziland - Consumer Price Index Cpi
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2012=100, NSA

Source: Central Bank of Swaziland

name: Swaziland - Inflation Rate
description:
The growth rate of the prices in Swaziland.

Units: percent Dec 2012=100

Source: Central Bank of Swaziland

name: Swaziland - Corporate Tax Rate
description:
The top marginal tax rate on corporate profits in Swaziland.

Units: percent

Source: Ministry of Finance

name: Swaziland - Exports
description:
The total value of the goods and services produced by Swaziland and purchased by foreign entities.

Units: SZL Million

Source: Central Bank of Swaziland

name: Swaziland - Foreign Direct Investment
description:
The value of all investments made by foreign entities directly into companies in Swaziland. It does not include foreign purchases of equities on domestic stock exchanges.

The monthly net financial position of Thailand in the global goods and services market, measured as the difference in value between its imports and exports. A negative trade balance indicates imports exceed exports; a positive trade balance indicates exports exceed imports.

Units: USD Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: Ministry of Commerce, Thailand

name: Thailand - Current Account
description:
The the sum of the balance of trade (goods and services exports less imports), net income from abroad and net current transfers. A positive value indicates that a country is a net lender to the rest of the world; a negative value indicates that a country is a net borrower.

Units: USD Million

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Current Account to GDP
description:
The current account balance of Thailand expressed as a percentage of its GDP.

Units: percent

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - New Car Registrations
description:
The number of new car registrations per month in Thailand.

Units: Volume, NSA

Source: Department of Land Transport, Thailand

name: Thailand - Consumer Credit
description:
The amount of money owed by residents of a country, including mortgages, bank loans, credit card and other debt.

Units: THB Million

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Core Consumer Prices
description:
This index tracks prices of consumer goods excluding food, energy and other items with high price volatility.

Units: Index Points 2015=100, NSA

Source: Bureau of Trade and Economic Indices, Thailand

name: Thailand - Competitiveness Index
description:
A measurement of the level of productivity of Thailand, based on a set of institutions, policies and other factors.

Units: Points

Source: World Economic Forum

name: Thailand - Coincident Index
description:
This weighted index of macroeconomic indicators tracks the health of Japan's regional economies. It consists of eleven leading indicators, eleven coincident indicators, and six lagged indicators. Positive values indicate economic expansion; negative values indicate economic contraction.

Units: Index Points 2000=100, SA

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Core Inflation Rate
description:
The rate of change of the core Consumer Price Index of Thailand.

Units: percent

Source: Bureau of Trade and Economic Indices, Thailand

name: Thailand - Consumer Confidence
description:
This monthly index tracks consumers' opinions about their current economic well-being and outlook for the economy. It provides insight into consumers' short-term spending, saving, and borrowing plans.

Units: Index Points

Source: University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce

name: Thailand - Consumer Price Index (CPI)
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2015=100, NSA

Source: Bureau of Trade and Economic Indices, Thailand

name: Thailand - Inflation Rate
description:
The growth rate of the prices in Thailand.

Units: percent NSA

Source: Bureau of Trade and Economic Indices, Ministry of Commerce, Thailand

name: Thailand - Inflation Rate Mom
description:
The monthly percent change consumer prices of Thailand.

Units: percent NSA

Source: Bureau of Trade and Economic Indices, Ministry of Commerce, Thailand

name: Thailand - Consumer Spending
description:
Total quarterly personal expenditure on goods and services in Thailand, excluding interest payments, land purchases, transfers abroad, business expenditures, and purchases of second-hand goods.

Units: THB Million Constant Prices 2002, NSA

Source: Nesdb, Thailand

name: Thailand - Corporate Tax Rate
description:
The top marginal tax rate on corporate profits in Thailand.

Units: percent

Source: The Revenue Department, Government of Thailand

name: Thailand - Capacity Utilization
description:
The monthly national output of Thailand as a percentage of its potential national output.

Units: Index Points SA, 2000=100

Source: Office of Industrial Economics, Thailand

name: Thailand - Changes in Inventories
description:
The quarterly change in inventory levels in Thailand.

Units: THB Million Constant Prices, NSA

Source: Nesdb, Thailand

name: Thailand - Households Disposable Income
description:
The household income remaining after taxes, deductions and interest payments, used for consumption and saving.

Units: THB Million

Source: Nesdb, Thailand

name: Thailand - Total Gross External Debt
description:
The total amount of public and private debt in Thailand owned by foreign creditors.

Units: USD Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Employed Persons
description:
The total number of employed (including self-employed) persons in Thailand.

Units: Thousand Volume, NSA

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Export Prices
description:
This monthly index tracks changes in the average price of exports in Thailand. The value of this index is the current price level expressed as a percentage of the price level from 2000. The index rises if exports become more expensive and falls if they get cheaper.

Units: Index Points NSA, 2012=100

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Exports
description:
The total value of the goods and services produced by Thailand and purchased by foreign entities.

Units: USD Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: Ministry of Commerce, Thailand

name: Thailand - Foreign Direct Investment
description:
The value of all investments made by foreign entities directly into companies in Thailand. It does not include foreign purchases of equities on domestic stock exchanges.

Units: THB Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Foreign Exchange Reserves
description:
The market value of the foreign currency reserves held by Thailand.

Units: USD Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - GDP
description:
The unadjusted gross domestic product of Thailand.

Units: USD Billion Current USD

Source: World Bank Group

name: Thailand - GDP Annual Growth Rate
description:
The annual growth rate of GDP in Thailand.

Units: percent

Source: Nesdb, Thailand

name: Thailand - Government Budget
description:
The federal government budget of Thailand as a percentage of its GDP. Negative values denote budget deficits; positive values denote budget surpluses.

Units: percent of GDP

Source: Ministry of Finance, Thailand

name: Thailand - Government Budget Value
description:
The balance of the federal budget of Thailand. It consists of tax revenues and expenses on government services. Negative budget values denote budget deficits; positive budget values denote budget surpluses.

Units: THB Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: Bank Of Thailand

name: Thailand - GDP Constant Prices
description:
An inflation-adjusted measure of GDP in the Thailand.

Units: THB Million Constant Prices, NSA

Source: Nesdb, Thailand

name: Thailand - GDP Deflator
description:
The relative difference between the real and nominal GDPs of Thailand.

Units: Index Points NSA, 2002=100

name: Thailand - Government Debt to GDP
description:
Government debt in Thailand as a percentage of its GDP.

Units: percent

Source: Ministry of Finance, Thailand

name: Thailand - Gross Fixed Capital Formation
description:
The net value of fixed capital flowing into businesses in Thailand, where fixed capital is the value of new fixed capital purchased by businesses less old fixed capital sold or disposed of, ignoring depreciation costs of existing fixed assets.

Units: THB Million Constant Prices 2002, NSA

Source: Nesdb, Thailand

name: Thailand - GDP Growth Rate
description:
The growth rate of the GDP of Thailand.

Units: percent

Source: Nesdb, Thailand

name: Thailand - Gross National Product
description:
The total value of all the final goods and services produced by residents of Thailand at home and abroad.

Units: THB Billion Constant Prices, NSA

Source: Nesdb, Thailand

name: Thailand - Gold Reserves
description:
The market value of the gold reserves held by the central bank of Thailand.

Units: Tonnes

Source: World Gold Council

name: Thailand - GDP per capita
description:
Gross Domestic Product per capita

name: Thailand - GDP per capita PPP
description:
GDP per capita in International dollars

Units: USD

name: Thailand - Government Spending
description:

name: Thailand - Government Bond 10Y

The average of the yield on ten-year government bonds in Thailand.

name: Thailand - House Price Index
description:

name: Thailand - Import Prices
description:
This monthly index tracks changes in import prices. The index rises if imports become more expensive and falls if they get cheaper.

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Imports

name: Thailand - Industrial Production

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Job Vacancies
description:

Units: Volume, NSA

Source: Bank of Thailand

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Leading Economic Index
description:
This index is comprised of ten leading economic indicators and is intended to predict the overall direction of the economy.

Units: Index Points 2000=100

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Loans to Private Sector
description:
The total value of bank loans to the private sector of Thailand.

Units: THB Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Money Supply M0
description:
The value of physical currency circulating in the economy and the liquid assets held by the central bank.

Units: THB Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: Bank of Thailand

name: Thailand - Money Supply M1
description:
M0 + the money in transactional bank accounts like checking accounts, demand deposits, and travelers' checks.

Units: THB Billion Current Prices, NSA

Source: Bank Of Thailand

name: Thailand - Money Supply M3

name: Thailand - Average Monthly Wages in Manufacturing

name: Thailand - Minimum Daily Wage

name: Thailand - Stock Market (SET50)
description:

name: Thailand - Manufacturing Pmi
description:
This monthly index tracks the health of the manufacturing sector in Thailand. Private sector companies report improvement or deterioration in key quantitative indicators like new orders, production, inventories, and employment levels. Responses are amalgamated into an index whose value indicates expansion or contraction of the manufacturing sector. A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

Source: Markit Economics

name: Thailand - Personal Income Tax Rate
description:

name: Thailand - Population
description:

Units: Million

name: Thailand - Producer Prices

The balance of the federal budget of South Africa. It consists of tax revenues and expenses on government services. Negative budget values denote budget deficits; positive budget values denote budget surpluses.

Units: ZAR Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - GDP Constant Prices
description:
An inflation-adjusted measure of GDP in the South Africa.

Units: ZAR Million Constant Prices, SA

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Government Debt to GDP
description:
Government debt in South Africa as a percentage of its GDP.

Units: percent

Source: National Treasury, South Africa

name: South Africa - Gross Fixed Capital Formation
description:
The net value of fixed capital flowing into businesses in South Africa, where fixed capital is the value of new fixed capital purchased by businesses less old fixed capital sold or disposed of, ignoring depreciation costs of existing fixed assets.

Units: ZAR Million Constant Prices, SA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - GDP Growth Rate
description:
The growth rate of the GDP of South Africa.

Units: percent

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Gross National Income
description:
The total income earned by residents of South Africa at home and abroad.

Units: ZAR Million Constant Prices, SA

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Gold Reserves
description:
The market value of the gold reserves held by the central bank of South Africa.

Units: Tonnes

Source: World Gold Council

name: South Africa - GDP per capita
description:
Gross Domestic Product per capita

Units: USD constant 2010 USD

Source: World Bank

name: South Africa - GDP per capita PPP
description:
GDP per capita in International dollars

Units: USD

Source: World Bank

name: South Africa - Government Spending
description:
The yearly expenditure of the federal government of South Africa.

Units: ZAR Million Constant Prices, SA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Government Bond 10Y
description:
The average of the yield on ten-year government bonds in South Africa.

Units: percent

Source: National Treasury, South Africa

name: South Africa - Three Month Interbank Rate
description:
The daily average of the interbank rate in South Africa. The interbank rate is the interest rate charged by banks on loans to other banks.

Units: percent

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Import Prices
description:
This quarterly index tracks changes in import prices. The index rises if imports become more expensive and falls if they get cheaper.

Units: Index Points SA, 2010=100

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Imports
description:
The total value of a country's imports of physical goods and payments to foreigners for services like shipping and tourism.

Units: ZAR Million

Source: South African Revenue Service

name: South Africa - Manufacturing Production
description:
The year-over-year percent change in the monthly industrial production of South Africa.

Units: percent 2015=100, NSA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Industrial Production MoM
description:
The monthly percent change in the industrial production of South Africa.

Units: percent 2015=100, SA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Interest Rate
description:
The daily average of the central bank policy rate in South Africa. This is the interest rate the central bank charges on loans to commercial banks.

Units: percent

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Labour Costs
description:
This quarterly index tracks changes in the share of labor in total production costs in South Africa. The index rises when the share of labor rises and falls when the share of labor falls.

Units: Index Points SA, 2010=100

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Labor Force Participation Rate
description:
The percentage of working-age persons in South Africa who are employed or seeking employment

Units: percent

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Loans to Private Sector
description:
The total value of bank loans to the private sector of South Africa.

Units: ZAR Million Current Prices, SA

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Money Supply M0
description:
The value of physical currency circulating in the economy and the liquid assets held by the central bank.

Units: ZAR Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Money Supply M1
description:
M0 + the money in transactional bank accounts like checking accounts, demand deposits, and travelers' checks.

Units: ZAR Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Money Supply M2
description:
M1 + savings deposits, small-denomination savings deposits, and retail money market mutual funds.

Units: ZAR Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Money Supply M3
description:
M2 + large-time deposits, institutional money market funds, short-term repurchase agreements and other larger liquid assets.

Units: ZAR Million Current Prices, SA

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Total Quarterly Wages in Manufacturing
description:
Total quarterly wages earned by the manufacturing sector of South Africa.

Units: ZAR/Month Current Prices, NSA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Mining Production
description:
Units: percent NSA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Stock Market
description:
A stock market index which tracks the performance of a selection of larger and more liquid companies based in South Africa.

Units: points

Source: Johannesburg Stock Exchange

name: South Africa - Manufacturing PMI
description:
This monthly index tracks the health of the manufacturing sector in South Africa. Private sector companies report improvement or deterioration in key quantitative indicators like new orders, production, inventories, and employment levels. Responses are amalgamated into an index whose value indicates expansion or contraction of the manufacturing sector. A PMI of 50% means equal numbers of respondents reported improvement and deterioration and there is no change from the previous month; PMIs above and below 50% indicate expansion and contraction of the sector respectively.

Source: Bureau for Economic Research (BER)

name: South Africa - Personal Income Tax Rate
description:
The top marginal tax rate on personal income in South Africa, including income earned from labor, pensions, interest, and dividends.

Units: percent

Source: South African Revenue Service

name: South Africa - Population
description:
The number of residents of South Africa.

Units: Million

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Producer Prices
description:
This index tracks the average prices domestic producers receive for their output in South Africa. These are the prices of final goods as they leave the factory gate rather than the prices set by wholesalers and resellers.

Units: Index Points 2012=100, NSA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Producer Prices Change
description:
The monthly percent change in the Producer Prices Index of South Africa.

Units: percent 2012=100, NSA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Household Saving Ratio
description:
The total amount of income saved by households in South Africa.

Units: percent SA

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Private Sector Credit
description:
The monthly change in outstanding private debt in South Africa.

Units: percent

Source: South African Reserve Bank

name: South Africa - Retail Sales MoM
description:
The monthly percent change in total retail sales in South Africa.

Units: percent Constant Prices 2015, SA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Retail Sales YoY
description:
The per cent change in total monthly retail sales relative to one year earlier in South Africa.

Units: percent Constant Prices 2015

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Social Security Rate
description:
The tax on labor income in South Africa used to fund social assistance programs.

Units: percent

Source: South African Social Security Agency (SASSA)

name: South Africa - Social Security Rate For Companies
description:
The tax rate on corporate profits in South Africa used to fund social assistance programs.

Units: percent

Source: South African Social Security Agency (SASSA)

name: South Africa - Social Security Rate For Employees
description:
The tax on wages in South Africa used to fund social assistance programs.

Units: percent

Source: South African Social Security Agency (SASSA)

name: South Africa - Sales Tax Rate
description:
The federal sales tax rate on goods and services in South Africa.

Units: percent

Source: South African Revenue Service

name: South Africa - Tourist Arrivals
description:
The number of tourists visiting South Africa from foreign countries.

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Total Vehicle Sales
description:
The number of new vehicles sold in South Africa.

Units: NSA

Source: National Association of Automobile Manufacturers of South Africa

name: South Africa - Unemployed Persons
description:
The total members of the labor force of South Africa who are unemployed and actively seeking work.

Units: Thousand Volume, NSA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Unemployment Rate
description:
The percentage of the labor force of South Africa who are unemployed and actively seeking work.

Units: percent SA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: South Africa - Average Monthly Gross Wage
description:
Total quarterly wages earned by the labor force of South Africa.

Units: ZAR/Month Current Prices, NSA

Source: Statistics South Africa

name: Zambia - Balance of Trade
description:
The monthly net financial position of Zambia in the global goods and services market, measured as the difference in value between its imports and exports. A negative trade balance indicates imports exceed exports; a positive trade balance indicates exports exceed imports.

Units: ZMK Million

Source: Central Statistical Office, Zambia

name: Zambia - Current Account
description:
The the sum of the balance of trade (goods and services exports less imports), net income from abroad and net current transfers. A positive value indicates that a country is a net lender to the rest of the world; a negative value indicates that a country is a net borrower.

Units: USD Million Current Prices, NSA

Source: Bank of Zambia

name: Zambia - Current Account to GDP
description:
The current account balance of Zambia expressed as a percentage of its GDP.

Units: percent

Source: Bank of Zambia

name: Zambia - Competitiveness Index
description:
A measurement of the level of productivity of Zambia, based on a set of institutions, policies and other factors.

Units: Points

Source: World Economic Forum

name: Zambia - Composite PMI
description:
Units: SA

Source: Markit Economics

name: Zambia - Consumer Price Index Cpi
description:
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of inflation related to the cost of living. It tracks the prices of essential goods and services like food and healthcare, and weighs those price changes according to their relative importance. The overall change in prices is the inflation rate, which can be positive or negative. The standard CPI fails to account for price drops resulting from improved production technologies, so the chained CPI was crafted to allow for a continuously changing basket of goods.

Units: Index Points 2009=100, NSA

Source: Central Statistical Office, Zambia

name: Zambia - Inflation Rate
description:
The growth rate of the prices in Zambia.

Units: percent

Source: Central Statistical Office, Zambia

name: Zambia - Corporate Tax Rate
description:

Units: percent

Source: Zambia Revenue Authority

name: Zambia - Exports
description:

Source: Central Statistical Office, Zambia

name: Zambia - Foreign Direct Investment
description:

Source: Bank of Zambia

name: Zambia - Food Inflation

Units: percent
